e Houston area, school and game officials decided to relocate the game to New Orleans.<ref>https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2017/8/27/16210992/hurricane-harvey-lsu-byu-game-houston-2017</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Further|2017 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings}}\n{{NCAA Division I FBS CFP ranking movements\n| year            = {{2017}}\n| finalpollweek   = 15\n| cfpfirstweek    = 9\n| AP_pre          = 13\n| coaches_pre     = 12\n| AP_1            = 12\n| coaches_1       = 12\n| AP_2            = 12\n| coaches_2       = 11\n| AP_3            = 25\n| coaches_3       = 23\n| AP_4            = 25\n| coaches_4       = 22\n| AP_5            = NR\n| coaches_5       = NR\n| AP_6            = RV\n| coaches_6       = RV\n| AP_7            = 24\n| coaches_7       = 25\n| AP_8            = 23\n| coaches_8       = 23\n| AP_9            = 23\n| coaches_9       = 23\n| cfp_9           = NR\n| AP_10           = 19\n| coaches_10      = 20\n| cfp_10          = 19\n| AP_11           = RV\n| coaches_11      = 25\n| cfp_11          = 24\n| AP_12           = 21\n| coaches_12      = 21\n| cfp_12          = 20\n| AP_13           = 19\n| coaches_13      = 18\n| cfp_13          = 18\n| AP_14           = 16\n| coaches_14      = 14\n| cfp_14          = 17\n| AP_15           = 18\n| coaches_15      = 18\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{LSU Tigers football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2017 LSU Tigers Football Team}}\n[[Category:2017 Southeastern Conference football season|LSU]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football seasons]]\n[[Category:2017 in sports in Louisiana|LSU Tigers f]]\n", "name_user": "Debartolo2917", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRoster", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2017_LSU_Tigers_football_team"}
{"title_page": "Alvin and the Chipmunks in film", "text_new": "{{Infobox media franchise\n| title         = ''Alvin and the Chipmunks''\n| image         = Alvin and the Chipmunks (film) logo.png\n| imagesize     = 250px\n| creator       = [[Ross Bagdasarian Sr.]]\n| origin        = [[Alvin and the Chipmunks]]\n| owner       = [[Ross Bagdasarian Jr.]]\n| films         = \n* {{nowrap|''[[The Chipmunk Adventure]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[Alvin and the Chipmunks (film)|Alvin and the Chipmunks]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel|The Squeakquel]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked|Chipwrecked]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Road Chip|The Road Chip]]''}}\n| soundtracks = \n* [[The_Chipmunk_Adventure#Soundtrack|The Chipmunk Adventure]]\n* [[Little_Alvin_and_the_Mini-Munks#Soundtrack|Little Alvin and the mini-Munks]]\n* [[Alvin_and_the_Chipmunks_(film)#Soundtrack|Alvin and the Chipmunks]]\n* [[Alvin_and_the_Chipmunks:_The_Squeakquel#Soundtrack|The Squeakquel]]\n* [[Alvin_and_the_Chipmunks:_Chipwrecked#Soundtrack|Chipwrecked]]\n* [[Alvin_and_the_Chipmunks:_The_Road_Chip#Soundtrack|The Road Chip]]  \n| dtv           =\n* {{nowrap|''[[Alvin and the Chipmunks Meet Frankenstein|Meet Frankenstein]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[Alvin and the Chipmunks Meet the Wolfman|Meet the Wolfman]]''}}\n* {{nowrap|''[[Little Alvin and the Mini-Munks]]''}}\n| italic_title=no\n| music = Scores composed by <br />[[Mark Mothersbaugh]]\n| otherlabel3 = First aired\n| otherdata3 = \n| otherlabel4 = Last aired\n| otherdata4  = \n| otherlabel5 = Distributor\n| otherdata5 = \n| otherlabel6 = First Film\n| otherdata6 = \n| otherlabel7 = Last Film\n| otherdata7 =\n}}\nThe fictional animated singing group '''Alvin and the Chipmunks''' created by [[Ross Bagdasarian Sr.]] have appeared in eight feature-length films since their debut. Their musical style is often considered to fall under the genres \"[[doom metal]]\", \"[[funeral doom]]\", and \"[[grindcore]]\".\n\n==Films==\n===Theatrical films===\n\n====''The Chipmunk Adventure'' (1987)====\n{{Main|The Chipmunk Adventure}}\nWhen [[David Seville]] goes off to [[Europe]] on a business trip, [[Alvin and the Chipmunks|the Chipmunks]], Alvin, Simon and Theodore, are left at home with their babysitter, Miss Beatrice Miller. While the three are playing an arcade game of ''Around the World in Thirty Days'' with [[the Chipettes]], Alvin and Brittany argue over which would win an actual race around the world, since Brittany beat Alvin in the video game. [[Diamond]] [[smugglers]] Claudia and Klaus Furschtein overhear the conversation and approach the children, telling them that they will provide them with the means for a real race around the world by [[hot air balloon]], with the winner receiving $100,000.\n\n====''Alvin and the Chipmunks'' (2007)====\n{{Main|Alvin and the Chipmunks (film)}}\nIn a tree farm, three musically inclined chipmunks, Alvin ([[Justin Long]]), the mischievous troublemaker, Simon ([[Matthew Gray Gubler]]), the smart one in the trio, and Theodore ([[Jesse McCartney]]) the chubby sweethearted chipmunk, find their tree cut down and are transported to Los Angeles. Once there, they meet frustrated songwriter David Seville ([[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]]), and despite a poor house-wrecking first impression, they impress him with their singing talent. Seeing the opportunity for success, both human and chipmunks make a pact for them to sing his songs. While that ambition proves a frustrating struggle with the difficult trio, the dream does come true after all. However, that success presents its own trials as their unscrupulous record executive, Ian Hawke ([[David Cross]]), plans to break up this family to exploit the boys. Can Dave and the Chipmunks discover what they really value amid the superficial glamour around them?\n\n====''Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel'' (2009)====\n{{Main|Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel}}\nPop sensations Alvin ([[Justin Long]]), Simon ([[Matthew Gray Gubler]]) and Theodore ([[Jesse McCartney]]) end up in the care of Dave Seville ([[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]])'s twenty-something cousin Toby ([[Zachary Levi]]). The boys must put aside music super stardom to return to school, and are tasked with saving the school's music program by winning the $25,000 prize in a battle of the bands. But the Chipmunks unexpectedly meet their match in three singing chipmunks known as The Chipettes\u2014Brittany ([[Christina Applegate]]), Jeanette ([[Anna Faris]]) and Eleanor ([[Amy Poehler]]). Romantic and musical sparks are ignited when the Chipmunks and Chipettes square off.\n\n====''Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked'' (2011)====\n{{Main|Alvin and the Chipmunks: Chipwrecked}}\nDave ([[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]]), the Chipmunks, and the Chipettes enjoy fun and mischief on a luxury cruise before their seafaring vacation takes an unexpected detour to an uncharted island. Now, the harder Alvin ([[Justin Long]]) and friends search for a way back to civilization, the more obvious it becomes that they aren't alone on this secluded island paradise.\n\n====''Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Road Chip'' (2015)====\n{{Main|Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Road Chip}}\nThrough a series of misunderstandings, Alvin ([[Justin Long]]), Simon ([[Matthew Gray Gubler]]) and Theodore ([[Jesse McCartney]]) come to believe that Dave ([[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]]) is going to propose to his new girlfriend in Miami...and dump them. They have three days to get to him and stop the proposal, saving themselves not only from losing Dave but possibly from gaining a terrible stepbrother.\n\n===Direct-to-video films===\n\n====''Alvin and the Chipmunks Meet Frankenstein'' (1999)====\n{{Main|Alvin and the Chipmunks Meet Frankenstein}}\nWhen the Chipmunks take a break from their concert, they get lost, and eventually get locked inside the park. They find their way to the \"Frankenstein's Castle\" attraction, where a real [[Victor Frankenstein|Dr. Victor Frankenstein]] is working on his [[Frankenstein's monster|monster]]. The monster is brought to life, and the doctor sends it in pursuit of the Chipmunks. In their escape, the monster retrieves Theodore's dropped [[teddy bear]]. Now it's up to the Chipmunks to get back his teddy bear and do something to the monster.\n\n====''Alvin and the Chipmunks Meet the Wolfman'' (2000)====\n{{Main|Alvin and the Chipmunks Meet the Wolfman}}\nWhen Alvin has nightmares of meeting the [[Werewolf|Wolfman]], which led him waking up screaming in horror, Simon and Dave conclude that Alvin's been watching too many horror films at night. Alvin says that it is because their new neighbor, [[Larry Talbot|Lawrence Talbot]], creeps him out and speculates that he is hiding something. Theodore is having trouble with Nathan, a bully, and will not go to the principal, who plans to retire due to Alvin's daily mishaps, for help; Alvin sticks up for him, however.\n\n====''Little Alvin and the Mini-Munks'' (2003)====\n{{Main|Little Alvin and the Mini-Munks}}\nLa-Lu, a friend of David Seville, has put up a banner saying \"Welcome Chipmunks\" on the porch of her magic cottage. One of her friends, Gilda (a talking pessimistic  [[cockatoo]]) believes that having children around is a bad idea. PC (a talking laid back [[frog]] with a surfer dude accent who believes he is one kiss away from being [[Prince Charming]]) says that his mom used to say \"nothing warms up a home like children's laughter\". Dave arrives with Alvin, Brittany, Simon, Jeanette, Theodore, and Eleanor. Dave needs the weekend to himself to write a new song, and La-Lu is happy to have five pre-schoolers and a baby stay with her and her friends. Sam and Lou, two [[gopher (animal)|gophers]], report to the viewers at home about the feelings the characters are experiencing via going into their heads and viewing an abstract inner visual manifestation of what the characters are thinking and or feeling. Alvin doesn't like that Dave is gone, and La-Lu explains that she felt the same way when she was little and reassures him that Dave will return for him and the others soon.\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office performance===\n\nThe live action animated films are the [[List of highest grossing live-action/animated films#Highest-grossing live-action/animated film franchises and series|highest-grossing live-action/animated film series]] and [[List of highest-grossing musicals|6th highest-grossing musicals film series]] of all time. The first film ranks as the [[List of highest grossing live-action/animated films#Highest-grossing films|5th highest grossing live-action/animated film]] of all time, with its sequels being ranked 4th, 7th, and 17th of all time. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"width:99%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Film\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Release date\n! colspan=\"3\" | Revenue\n! colspan=\"2\" | Box office ranking\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Budget\n! rowspan=\"2\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! U.S. and Canada\n! Other territories\n! Worldwide\n! U.S. and Canada\n! Worldwide\n|-\n|''The Chipmunk Adventure''\n|{{start date|1987|5|22}}\n|$6,804,312 \n| style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|$6,804,312\n|#5,147\n| style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n| style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n| <ref>{{cite web|title= the Chipmunks Adventure(1987)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=chipmunkadventure.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=February 23, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Alvin and the Chipmunks''\n|{{start date|2007|12|14}}\n|$217,326,974 \n|$144,009,659\n|$361,336,633\n| #163\n| #322\n|$60 millon\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Alvin and the Chipmunks (2007)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=alvinandthechipmunks.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=February 23, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Squeakquel''\n|{{start date|2009|12|23}}\n|$219,614,612\n|$223,525,393\n|$443,140,005\n|#154\n|#229\n|$75 million\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Alvin and the Chipmu