{"title_page": "Loch Tarff", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{coord|57.1537|-4.6042|display=title}}\n\n\n'''Loch Tarff''' is a small freshwater [[loch]] approximately {{convert|1.25|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the southeastern shore of [[Loch Ness]] in the [[Scottish Highlands]]. \n\n==Geography and Geology==\nThe loch is located in the hills that rise steeply from the eastern shore of Loch Ness and has an elevation of {{convert|292|metres|feet}} ASL. It has a surface area of approximately 500,000 square metres with a prominent inlet to the northwest and a smaller inlet to the southwest. The loch is fed by a number of small streams, most of which enter its northeastern shore from the southern slopes of Beinn a' Bhacaidh. There are a number of [[Islet|islets]] in the loch, the largest of which, Eilean Ban, lies near its northeastern shore.<ref>{{cite web |URL=https://getoutside.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/local/loch-tarff-highland |title=Loch Tarff, Highland (PH32 4BZ) |publisher= Ordnance Survey |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nGeological evidence indicates that the loch was formed in the last [[Ice age|Ice Age]] approximately 10,000 years ago, and is the result of [[Glacial period|glaciation]] that scoured the landscape. The surrounding rock is [[Metamorphic rock|metamorphic]], mostly [[Schist|schists]], although there are also [[Sedimentary rock|sedimentary]] [[Conglomerate (geology)|conglomerates]] formed from the metamorphic and [[Igneous rock|igneous]] strata in the [[Fault scarp|fault scarp]] that comprises the [[Great Glen]]. Glacial sediments can be found to the south of the loch around the southern shore of Loch Ness.<ref>{{cite web |URL=http://www.nessie.co.uk/htm/about_loch_ness/nessgeo.html |title=A Geological View of Loch Ness and Area |publisher=Legend of Nessie |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Access==\nBy car, the loch is approximately {{convert|6.0|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[Fort Augustus]], and is accessible by the B862 road, which runs along the eastern shore of the loch.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Fort+Augustus/Loch+Tarff,+Fort+Augustus+IV2+6UP/@57.1460152,-4.6459079,14z/am=t/data=!4m14!4m13!1m5!1m1!1s0x488f210df41b3beb:0x12170f9721af3cd0!2m2!1d-4.6805166!2d57.1448064!1m5!1m1!1s0x488f22e2bedb69c3:0x488f22e2c7f7967e!2m2!1d-4.606506!2d57.1529851!3e0 |title=Directions Fort Augustus to Loch Tarff |publisher=Google Maps |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFor walkers, the loch is located on the [[South Loch Ness Trail]], approximately one and a half to two hours via an ascending route that rises {{convert|280|metres|feet}} with two moderate inclines from the southern shore of Loch Ness at Fort Augustus.<ref>{{cite web |URL=https://osmaps.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/57.15089,-4.59219,15 |title=OS Maps Route Planner|publisher= Ordnance Survey |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances in Media==\n\nFootage of the loch was used in the 1983 film [[Local Hero (film)|Local Hero]] (in the scene immediately following the rabbit and the fog).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotlandthemovie.com/movies/lhtaff.html |title=Scotland: the Movie Location Guide |publisher=Doug Hill |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Freshwater lochs of Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{coord|57.1537|-4.6042|display=title}}\n\n\n'''Loch Tarff''' is a small freshwater [[loch]] approximately {{convert|1.25|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the southeastern shore of [[Loch Ness]] in the [[Scottish Highlands]]. \n\n==Geography and Geology==\nThe loch is located in the hills that rise steeply from the eastern shore of Loch Ness and has an elevation of {{convert|292|metres|feet}} ASL. It has a surface area of approximately 500,000 square metres with a prominent inlet to the northwest and a smaller inlet to the southwest. The loch is fed by a number of small streams, most of which enter its northeastern shore from the southern slopes of Beinn a' Bhacaidh. There are a number of [[Islet|islets]] in the loch, the largest of which, Eilean Ban, lies near its northeastern shore.<ref>{{cite web |URL=https://getoutside.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/local/loch-tarff-highland |title=Loch Tarff, Highland (PH32 4BZ) |publisher= Ordnance Survey |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nGeological evidence indicates that the loch was formed in the last [[Ice age|Ice Age]] approximately 10,000 years ago, and is the result of [[Glacial period|glaciation]] that scoured the landscape. The surrounding rock is [[Metamorphic rock|metamorphic]], mostly [[Schist|schists]], although there are also [[Sedimentary rock|sedimentary]] [[Conglomerate (geology)|conglomerates]] formed from the metamorphic and [[Igneous rock|igneous]] strata in the [[Fault scarp|fault scarp]] that comprises the [[Great Glen]]. Glacial sediments can be found to the south of the loch around the southern shore of Loch Ness.<ref>{{cite web |URL=http://www.nessie.co.uk/htm/about_loch_ness/nessgeo.html |title=A Geological View of Loch Ness and Area |publisher=Legend of Nessie |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Access==\nBy car, the loch is approximately {{convert|6.0|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[Fort Augustus]], and is accessible by the B862 road, which runs along the eastern shore of the loch.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Fort+Augustus/Loch+Tarff,+Fort+Augustus+IV2+6UP/@57.1460152,-4.6459079,14z/am=t/data=!4m14!4m13!1m5!1m1!1s0x488f210df41b3beb:0x12170f9721af3cd0!2m2!1d-4.6805166!2d57.1448064!1m5!1m1!1s0x488f22e2bedb69c3:0x488f22e2c7f7967e!2m2!1d-4.606506!2d57.1529851!3e0 |title=Directions Fort Augustus to Loch Tarff |publisher=Google Maps |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFor walkers, the loch is located on the [[South Loch Ness Trail]], approximately one and a half to two hours via an ascending route that rises {{convert|280|metres|feet}} with two moderate inclines from the southern shore of Loch Ness at Fort Augustus.<ref>{{cite web |URL=https://osmaps.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/57.15089,-4.59219,15 |title=OS Maps Route Planner|publisher= Ordnance Survey |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances in Media==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Loch Tarff (Local Hero).jpg|thumb|400px|Loch Tarff, as it appears in ''Local Hero'']] -->\n\nFootage of the loch was used in the 1983 film [[Local Hero (film)|Local Hero]] (in the scene immediately following the rabbit and the fog).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotlandthemovie.com/movies/lhtaff.html |title=Scotland: the Movie Location Guide |publisher=Doug Hill |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The scene is taken from the B862 looking westward. Some of the loch's islets can be see in the background.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Freshwater lochs of Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Blammy1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAppearances in Media", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loch_Tarff"}
